{"title_page": "Gujarati Muslims", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious group\n|group = Gujarati Muslim\n|image = \n|caption = \n|population =  {{Circa|'''6.8 million'''|lk=yes}}{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n|region1 = {{flag|India}}\n|pop1    = 5,800,000 \n|ref1    = <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/Religion_PCA.html|title=Census of India Website : Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|website=www.censusindia.gov.in|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n| region2 = {{flag|Pakistan}}\n| pop2    = 1,000,000\n| ref2    = <ref name=e20>{{e20|guj}}</ref>\n|poptime = \n|popplace =  [[India]], [[Pakistan]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[South Africa]], [[Kenya]], [[Tanzania]], [[Uganda]], [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Madagascar]]\n|langs = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]],<ref name=omniglot>{{cite web|title=Gujar\u0101t\u012b|url=http://www.omniglot.com/writing/gujarati.htm|publisher=Onmiglot: online encyclopaedia of writing systems and languages|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> [[Urdu]]\n|rels=  [[Islam]]\n}}\n\nThe term '''Gujarati Muslims''' is usually used to signify an Indian [[Muslim]] from the state of [[Gujarat]] in western coast of India.  Gujarati Muslims are very prominent in industry and medium-sized businesses, and there is a very large Gujarati Muslim community in [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Patel|first1=edited by Sujata|last2=Masselos|first2=Jim|title=Bombay and Mumbai : the city in transition|date=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New Delhi|isbn=0195663179|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jmPuAAAAIAAJ&q=gujarati+muslims+in+mumbai&dq=gujarati+muslims+in+mumbai}}</ref>. Gujrati Muslim are termed as the richest Muslims in India and Pakistan as well. Many members of this community migrated to [[Pakistan]] in 1947 and have settled in [[Sindh]] province especially in [[Karachi]], contributing to the national welfare and economy of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Laurent Gayer|title=Karachi : ordered disorder and the struggle for the city|date=2014|isbn=978-0-19-935444-3|page=300|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BklRBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA300&dq=gujaratis,+memons,+pakistan#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20memons%2C%20pakistan&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=Out of Pakistan's forty-two largest industrial groups, thirty-six were in the hands of Karachi-based businessmen - generally members of the Gujarati/Kutchi/Kathiawari trading sects, both Sunni (Memon) and Shia (Khojas, Bohras, etc.)  Whereas they accounted for 0.4 per cent of Pakistan's total population, Gujarati trading groups (they are considered [[Muhajir people|Muhajir]] since many of their members were already settled in Karachi before the independence) controlled 43 per cent of the country's industrial capital. Halai Memons alone (0.3 per cent of the national population) owned 27 per cent of these industries. And while he patronised Pashtun entrepreneurs in Karachi, Ayub Khan also relied upon Gujarati businessmen to finance his electoral campaign in 1964, while facilitating the entry into politics of some Muhajir entrepreneurs, such as Sadiq Dawood, a Memon industrialist who became an MNA,  and the Treasurer of Ayub's Convention Muslim League.}}</ref> Having earned a formidable accolade as some of India's greatest seafaring merchants,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peck|first1=Amelia|title=Interwoven Globe: The Worldwide Textile Trade, 1500-1800|publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York|isbn=978-1-58839-496-5|page=15|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BYjh82N63IQC&pg=PA15&dq=gujarati+merchants,+red+sea#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20merchants%2C%20red%20sea&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Of the Asian trading communities the most successful were the Gujaratis, as witnessed not only by Pires and Barbosa but by a variety of other sources. All confirm that merchants from the Gujarati community routinely held the most senior post open to an expatriate trader, that of shah-bandar (controller of maritime trade).|year=2013}}</ref> the centuries-old Gujarati diaspora is found scattered throughout the ''Near East, Indian Ocean, and Southern Hemisphere'' regions everywhere in between Africa and Japan with a notable presence in:<ref>{{cite web|title=Where on earth do they speak Gujarati?|url=http://www.verbix.com/maps/language/Gujarati.html|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> [[Hong Kong]],<ref>{{cite book|authors=ed. by Robert Bickers|title=New frontiers : imperialism's new communities in East Asia, 1842-1953|date=2000|publisher=Manchester Univ. Press|location=Manchester [u.a.]|isbn=0-7190-5604-7|page=67|edition=1. publ.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OmW7AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA67&dq=gujarati+muslims,+hong+kong#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20muslims%2C%20hong%20kong&f=false|quote=The 1889 Hong Kong Directory and Hong List for the Far East lists three Sindhi firms in Hong Kong among a total of thirty-one firms, of which the majority were Parsi and Gujarati Muslim.}}</ref> [[United Kingdom|Britain]], [[Portugal]], [[R\u00e9union]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Nandita Dutta|title=An Indian Reunion|url=http://www.littleindia.com/life/12041-an-indian-reunion.html|website=littleindia.com|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Raziah Locate is a manager in a hospitality school. Her grandfather Omarjee Ismael embarked on a voyage with his wife in 1870 from Kathor, near Surat, in Gujarat. He came to Reunion Island to seek better opportunities to further his trade in clothing. Her grandfather was one of the 40,000 merchants, traders and artisans from Gujarat who are said to have voluntary migrated to Reunion Island starting in the 1850s. Her grandfather was one of the pioneers who paved the way for other Gujarati Muslims to settle in Reunion, who have built a mosque and a madrasa on the island.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716114621/http://www.littleindia.com/life/12041-an-indian-reunion.html|archive-date=16 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Oman]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Hugh Eakin|title=In the Heart of Mysterious Oman|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/aug/14/heart-mysterious-oman/|website=The New York Review of Books|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=August 14, 2014}}</ref> [[Yemen]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Nafeesa Syeed|title=Learning Gujarati in Yemen|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2012/09/24/learning-gujarati-in-yemen/|website=indiarealtime.com|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Mr. Haji, clad in the gold-trimmed, white cap that is standard for Bohra men, was in a flurry on a recent Friday, as he catered to streams of constituents and answered phone calls. He slid effortlessly between Arabic, Urdu, English and Dawat ni zabaan\u2014a strain of Gujarati particular to Bohras that is peppered with Arabic and Persian. He explained that they have other shrines in Yemen, but this is one of the most important. Some 10,000 Bohras, mostly from India but also from their populations in Pakistan, East Africa, the United States, Europe and the Middle East, travel here each year.}}</ref> [[Mozambique]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Nazar Abbas|title=Pakistanis who have never seen Pakistan|url=http://www.thefridaytimes.com/tft/pakistanis-who-have-never-seen-pakistan/|website=The Friday Times|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=After ties broke down between India and Portugal, Gujarati Muslims stranded in Mozambique were given Pakistani citizenship...Merchants from Diu had settled on the island of Mozambique in the early 1800s. Hindus from Diu, Sunni Muslims from Daman, and others from Goa migrated to Mozambique as small traders, construction workers and petty employees. Many Gujaratis moved from South Africa to Mozambique in the latter half of the 19th century.}}</ref> [[Zanzibar]],<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ababu Minda Yimene|title=An African Indian Community in Hyderabad: Siddi Identity, Its Maintenance and Change|date=2004|isbn=3-86537-206-6|pages=66, 67|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DigPvwHTqJ4C&pg=PA67&dq=gujaratis+in+england,+19th+century#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%20in%20england%2C%2019th%20century&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Some centuries later, the Gujarati merchants established permanent trading posts in Zanzibar, consolidating their influence in the Indian Ocean... Gujarati Muslims, and their Omani partners, engaged in a network of mercantile activities among Oman, Zanzibar and Bombay. Thanks to those mercantile Gujarati, India remained by far the principal trading partner of Zanzibar.}}</ref> [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Myanmar|Burma]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Dr Asghar Ali Engineer |title=Rohingya Muslims in Myanmar and recent riots - an Aman Report |url=http://www.csss-isla.com/arch-July-1-15-2012.htm |website=Centre for study of society and secularism |accessdate=9 February 2015 |quote=Lot of Muslims had gone from Surat and still there is a beautiful Surti mosque. Muslims in Myanmar are highly diverse. There are very few ethnic Burmese Muslims, most of them are migrants from different parts of India when Burma was a part of India. There are large number of Tamil, Gujarati and Bengali and Bohra Muslims and very few Urdu speaking Muslims since Urdu speaking are not in business. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209225842/http://www.csss-isla.com/arch-July-1-15-2012.htm |archivedate=February 9, 2015 }}</ref> [[Madagascar]],<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pedro Machado|title=Ocean of Trade|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-07026-4|page=232|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ODfJBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA232&lpg=PA232&dq=gujarati+muslims,+madagascar#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20muslims%2C%20madagascar&f=false|quote=Gujarati merchants may also have financed slave voyages to Madagascar in the nineteenth century. They sailed to its west coast from the mid 1810s to the mid 1820s but do not appear to have become extensively involved in this trafficking, either as shippers or as financiers. This is likely explained by the increasing presence in coastal Madagascar of Khoja and Bohra Shi'ia merchants from Kutch who, together with the Bhatiya merchants, established a significant presence there as financiers of the slave trade from the second decade of the nineteenth century.|date=2014-11-06}}</ref> [[South Africa]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Mauritius]], [[Pakistan]], [[Zambia]] and [[East Africa]] \n\nAccording to the 2011 [[Census of India]], the Gujarati Muslim population was 5,846,761 but significant numbers of Gujarati Muslims are found within the larger context of the Gujarati diaspora that became established throughout all the inhabited continents of the world.{{cn|date=July 2019}}\n\nMost Gujarati Muslims have Gujarati language as their mother tongue, but some communities such as the [[Momin Ansari]], [[Memons]],<ref>Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency, Gujarat Population: Musalmans and Parsis, Volume IX pages 13 to 14 Government Central Press, Bombay</ref> [[Gujarati Shaikh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unescoparzor.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=15&Itemid=60 |title=Parzor &#124; The UNESCO Parsi Zoroastrian Project |publisher=Unescoparzor.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref><ref name=\"survey\">People of India Gujarat Volume XXII Part One Editors R. B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan and M Azeez Mohideen pages 74 to 77</ref> and others, have [[Urdu]] as their mother tongue.<ref>name=\"Indian Census 2001 - Religion\" [http://demotemp257.nic.in/httpdoc/Census_Data_2001/Census_data_finder/C_Series/Population_by_religious_communities.htm Indian Census 2001 - Religion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312153215/http://demotemp257.nic.in/httpdoc/Census_Data_2001/Census_data_finder/C_Series/Population_by_religious_communities.htm |date=2007-03-12 }}</ref>\n\nThe majority of Gujarati Muslims are Sunni, with a minority of heterodox Shi'ite groups.\n\nThe Gujarati Muslims are further sub-divided into groups, such as the [[Sunni Bohra|Sunni Vohra/Bohra]], [[Ismailism|Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl\u012b]], [[Khoja]], [[Dawoodi Bohra]], [[Memons (Kathiawar)|Memon]], [[Surti Muslims|Surti]], [[Pathan people]], [[Soomra (Muslim)|Khatri]], [[Ghanchi (Muslim)|Ghanchi]] and [[Chhipa]] each with their own customs and traditions.\n\nGujarati Muslims played a pivotal role in establishing [[Islam]] in [[Southeast Asia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gujarat helped establish Islam in SE Asia|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/ampnbspGujarat-helped-establish-Islam-in-SE-Asia/articleshow/11262585.cms|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|last=Prabhune|first=Tushar|location=[[Ahmedabad]]|date=December 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nLocated in the westernmost portion of India, Gujarat includes the region of [[Kutch]], [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]], and the territories between the rivers [[Banas River|Banas]] and [[Daman Ganga River|Damanganga]]. [[Islam]] came early to Gujarat, with immigrant communities of [[Arab]] and [[Persian people|Persian]] traders.  Most came as traders as they did before Islam and built a masjid during the times of Muhammad and other parts of the western seacoast of India as early as the 8th century C.E, spreading Islam soon as the religion gained a foothold in the Arabian peninsula.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Gokhale|title=Surat In The Seventeenth Century|publisher=Popular Prakashan|page=28|url=https://books.google.com/?id=frbYo91TuV4C&pg=PA28&dq=surat,+gujarat,+Islam,+muslim,+arab#v=onepage&q=surat%2C%20gujarat%2C%20Islam%2C%20muslim%2C%20arab&f=false|accessdate=23 February 2015|quote=Islam was introduced into Gujarat in the 7th century C.E. The first Arab raid came in 635 when the Governor of Bahrain sent an expedition against Broach. Then through the centuries colonies of Arab and Persian merchants began sprouting in the port cities of  Gujarat, such as Cambay, Broach and Surat.|isbn=9788171542208}}</ref> They were later joined by [[Persian people|Persian]] traders from [[Greater Iran]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mallison|first1=edited by Tazim R. Kassam, Fran\u00e7oise|title=Gin\u0101ns : texts and contexts : essays on Ismaili hymns from South Asia in honour of Zawahir Moir|date=2010|publisher=Primus Books|location=Delhi|isbn=978-8190891875|page=150|edition=Rev.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xmh3gQjPHkAC&pg=PA150&dq=PERSIAN+merchants,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=PERSIAN%20merchants%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=28 April 2015|quote=In the early period, it appears that the Ismailis in western India, consisted of ethnic Arab or Persian merchant settlers, as well as local converts from pastoralist, cultivating or merchant groups. They may have included militarised peasants and pastoralists from north-west India, some of whom went on to become part of the emerging Rajput status hierarchy... After the fall of Alamut to the Mongols in 1256, more Nizari missionaries came to Sind and Gujarat, Ucch in particular becoming an important centre.}}</ref> Many of these early merchants were [[Ismaili]] [[Shia]], both [[Mustaali]] and [[Nizari]]. They laid the foundation of the [[Mustaali|Bohra]] and [[Khoja]] communities. In the early era however Gujarat was ruled by the [[Valabhi]] dynasty. In the thirteenth century, the last [[Hindu]] ruler Karna, was defeated by [[Alauddin Khalji]], the [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] [[Delhi Sultanate|Sultan of Dehli]]. This episode ushered a period of five centuries of Muslim Turkic and [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] rule, leading to a conversion of a number of Hindu Gujarati people to [[Islam]], and the creation of new communities such as the [[Molesalam Rajput|Molesalam]] and [[Miyana (community)|Miyana]] communities.\n\nIn the sixteenth century, the [[Memon people|Memon]] community immigrated from [[Sindh]] and settled in Kutch and [[Kathiawar]]. While in [[Bharuch]] and [[Surat]], a [[Schism (religion)|schism]] occurred among the Bohras, and a new community of [[Sunni Bohra]]s was created. Another Muslim sect, the [[Mahdawi]] also settled in Gujarat, and led to the creation of the [[Tai (caste)|Tai]] community.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berkeley|first1=Ira M. Lapidus, University of California|title=A history of Islamic societies|date=2014|isbn=978-0521514309|page=399|edition=Third|quote=The Mahdawi movement was important in Gujarat in the sixteenth century and was widely accepted during the reign of Sultan Akbar by the administrative, military, landowning, and merchant elites.}}</ref> In 1593, the Mughal Emperor [[Akbar]] conquered Gujarat, and incorporated Gujarat in the Mughal Empire. This period led to the settlement of the [[Mughal (tribe)|Mughal]] community. A good many [[Sayyid of Gujarat|Sayyid]] and [[Gujarati Shaikh|Shaikh]] families also are said to have arrived during the period of Mughal rule. With the establishment of the Sufi [[Suhrawardiyya|Suhrawardi]] and [[Chishti]] orders in [[Multan]], Sind and Gujarat, [[pir (Sufism)|pirs]] enjoyed state patronage.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berkeley|first1=Ira M. Lapidus, University of California|title=A history of Islamic societies|date=2014|isbn=978-0521514309|page=399|edition=Third|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kFJNBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA399&dq=PERSIAN+merchants,+Islam,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=PERSIAN%20merchants%2C%20Islam%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> At the same time, the Muslims from various provinces such as [[Hyderabad Deccan]], [[Kerala]], Balochistan, Sindh, [[Punjab]], Gujarat, [[Kashmir]] and other parts of South Asia also moved to capitals of Muslim empire in [[Delhi]] and [[Agra]]. After the death of the Mughal emperor [[Aurangzeb]], in 1707, Mughal rule began weaken after ruling for a century. Most of Gujarat fell to the [[Maratha]]s, and this period saw the dispersal of further Pathans and Baluchis, who came as mercenaries and were destroyed or defeated by the [[Maratha]]s. Gujarat fell to [[United Kingdom|British]] in the late 19th century.<ref name=\"Muslim Peoples pages 294\">Muslim Peoples: A World Ethnographic Survey editor Richard V Weekes pages 294 to 297</ref>\n\nGujarati Muslim merchants played an historically important role in facilitating the Portuguese discovery of \"[[Indies|the East Indies]]\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Gujarati showed Vasco 'da' way|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-03/ahmedabad/28223775_1_gama-vasco-da-gujarati|publisher=The Times of India|accessdate=1 October 2013|date=Oct 3, 2010|quote=Historians have differed over the identity of the sailor, calling him a Christian, a Muslim and a Gujarati. According to another account, he was the famous Arab navigator Ibn Majid. Some historians suggest Majid could not have been near the vicinity at the time. German author Justus says it was Malam who accompanied Vasco...Italian researcher Sinthia Salvadori too has concluded that it was Malam who showed Gama the way to India. Salvadori has made this observation in her 'We Came In Dhows', an account written after interacting with people in Gujarat.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Homage to a Historian: A Festschrift|year=1976|publisher=Dr. N. Subrahmanian 60th Birthday Celebration Committee|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CbgBAAAAMAAJ&q=Kanji+Malam&dq=Kanji+Malam|authors=N. Subrahmanian, Tamil\u0332an\u0332pan\u0332, S. Jeyapragasam|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Rethinking solidarity in global society : the challenge of globalisation for social and solidarity movements : 50 years after Bandung Asian-African Conference 1955|year=2007|publisher=Strategic Information and Research Development Centre|location=Petaling Jaya, Selangor, Malaysia|isbn=9789833782130|page=35|url=https://books.google.com/?id=R6zZAAAAMAAJ&q=Kanji+Malam&dq=Kanji+Malam|author=Darwis Khudori|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref> in spreading and propagating Islam to the [[Far East]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Aritonang|first1=edited by Jan Sihar|last2=Steenbrink|first2=Karel|title=A history of Christianity in Indonesia|date=2008|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=978-90-04-17026-1|page=11|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cUoGJSs9yOUC&pg=PA11&dq=gujarati+muslims,+indonesia#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20muslims%2C%20indonesia&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=The predominant Muslim position in the international trade was also represented by Muslim outposts along the southern coast of the Indian subcontinent. They included Randir, Surat and Cambay (in Gujarat). In fact, they had been supposed to have not only played a significant role in international Muslim trade, but also in the spread of Islam, in supposedly in the Malay-Indonesian archipelago.}}</ref> and in promoting the British [[Exploration of Africa|discovery of Africa]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Achyut Yagnik, Suchitra Sheth|title=The shaping of modern Gujarat : plurality, Hindutva, and beyond|date=2005|publisher=Penguin Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=0-14400-038-5|page=25|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wmKIiAPgnF0C&pg=PA25&dq=gujaratis,+memons,+pakistan#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20memons%2C%20pakistan&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=After the opening up of East Africa in the nineteenth century, they became pioneers of trading activity there, dominating not only the financial world but also the political affairs of the region. Interestingly, it was these Gujarati Muslim traders along with Kutchi Bhatias who provided equipment, rations and financial services to European explorers such as, Stanley,  Livingstone, Burton and Cameron, and thus facilitated the 'discovery of Africa'}}</ref> In Southeast Asia, Malays referred to the Islamic elite among them by the noble title of adhirajas.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hall|first1=Kenneth R.|title=A History of Early Southeast Asia Maritime Trade and Societal Development, 100-1500.|date=2010|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Pub. Group|location=Lanham|isbn=978-0742567627|page=309|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fjsEn3w4TPgC&pg=PA309&dq=Persian+traders,+Muslims,+Gujarat#v=onepage&q=Persian%20traders%2C%20Muslims%2C%20Gujarat&f=false|accessdate=28 April 2015|quote=All the Gujarati merchants were Muslims, and the elite among them were termed adhiraja, a Malay title of nobility, seemingly as an acknowledgment that there was a local mix of the resident Gujarati merchant elite and the Malay political aristocracy.}}</ref> The [[Sufi]] trader, [[Nuruddin ar-Raniri|Shaikh Randeri]] (Shaikh Raneri) was responsible for spreading Islam to [[Acheh]] in [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Biographical Encyclopaedia of Sufis: South Asia |author=N. Hanif |publisher=Sarup & Sons |year=2000 |isbn=9788176250870 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=O3GXOqPa67MC&pg=PA326&lpg=PA326&dq=shaikh+raniri#v=onepage&q=shaikh%20raniri&f=false }}</ref> \nSurti merchants in particular also pioneered the use of scientific concepts, and invented structural and mechanical advances in technology for the nationbuilding of [[Mauritius]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Dukhira|first=Chit|title=The genuis<!-- sic -->: Amode Ibrahim Atchia, (1868-1947)|url=http://www.lexpress.mu/article/genuis-amode-ibrahim-atchia-1868-1947|publisher=lexpess.mu.online}}</ref> such as introducing [[hydro-electric power]] to the people of [[Mauritius]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Atchia|first=Dr. Michael|title=Major Atchia, a model of enterprise|url=http://www.lexpress.mu/article/%E2%80%9Cmajor%E2%80%9D-atchia-model-enterprise|publisher=lexpress.mu.online}}</ref>\n\n== Jamat Bandi ==\nGujarati speaking Muslim society has a unique custom known as '''Jamat Bandi''', literally meaning communal solidarity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Muslim communities of Gujarat|url=http://twocircles.net/2011may03/muslim_communities_gujarat.html#.VNjCr-asUbA|website=TwoCircles.net|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Muslims of Gujarat are probably the most diverse of Muslim population of any other Indian state. Some of them came from different parts of the Islamic world over a period of thousand years to seek security, employment, trade, and to spread Islam; bringing with them their culture, knowledge, and their own versions of Islam. Though there has been much interaction with different Muslim groups, the differences have survived to make Gujarati Muslims a very diverse ummah...First came the Arabs; within the first 100 years of revelation of Quran, there were a number of Muslim towns along the coast of Gujarat. They were followed by Iranians, Africans, and Central Asians. Earlier Muslims came as traders; some came with the invading armies and settled down. Many others came seeking better employment opportunities, while some like Bohras came here fleeing persecution.}}</ref> This system is the traditional expression of communal solidarity. It is designed to regulate the affairs of the community and apply sanctions against infractions of the communal code. Almost all the main Gujarat communities, such as the Ghanchi,[[Ismailism|Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl\u012b]],    [[Khoja]], [[Dawoodi Bohra]], [[Chhipa]], and [[Sunni Bohra]] have [[caste]] associations, known as jamats. Social organization at the Jamat Bandi level varies from community to community. In some communities, the Jamat simply runs a mosque and attached rest house, and a [[madrasah]]. Some larger communities, such as the [[Khoja]] and [[Memon people|Memon]] have developed elaborate and highly formalized systems with written and registered constitutions. Their organizations own large properties, undertake housing projects and schools, dispensaries and weekly newspapers.\n\n== Communities ==\nThe region of Kutch has always been historically distinct, with the Muslims there accounting for about twenty percent of the population. This region is characterised by salt deserts, such as the [[Rann of Kutch]]. Because of this landscape, the Kutch Muslims are [[Maldhari]] pastoral nomads found in the [[Banni Grasslands Reserve|Banni]] region of Kutch. Most of them are said to have originated in Sindh, and speak a dialect of [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] which has many [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] loanwords. Major [[Maldhari]] communities include the [[Sandhai Muslims]], [[Jats of Kutch|Jats]], [[Halaypotra]], [[Hingora]], [[Hingorja]], [[Junejo|Juneja]] and [[Samma (tribe)|Samma]] tribes.<ref>People of India Gujarat Volume XXI  Part  Two edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 487-491</ref> The other important Muslim community is the [[Memons (Kathiawar)|Khatiawari Memon]] community, that migrated and resettled beyond Gujarat state during partition of India in 1947.<ref>{{Citation|title=Memon people|date=2020-02-23|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Memon_people&oldid=942253688|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Khatiawari memon community is regarded as the wealthiest community in India and Pakistan. Mainly, due to their involvement in international trade and contribution to nations economy. [[Memons (Kathiawar)|Khatiawari memons]] are famous for their humanitarian services and other welfare services under the banner of [https://wmoworld.com/ World Memon Organization]. Khatiawari memons follow are also further divided under various surnames like Adamjee, Adani, Admani, Bagha, Bandukra, Chamadia, Dhedhi, Lakhani, Patel; [[Memons (Kathiawar)|Khatiawari memons]] proudly recall their rich history from their ansestral villages named [[Kutiyana]], [[Bantva]], [[Porbandar]] currently located in modern state of [[Gujarat]], [[India]].  \n\nThe Gujarat coastline is also home to significant numbers of [[Siddi]], otherwise known as ''Zanji'' or ''Habshi'', descendants of Africans e.g. [http://britishlibrary.typepad.co.uk/asian-and-african/2013/04/ikhlas-khan-the-african-prime-minister-of-bijapur.html Royal Habshis] (Abyssinian aristocracy e.g. [[Sidi Saiyyed Mosque|Siddi Sayyid]]), or [[Bantu peoples]] from Southeast Africa that were brought to the Indian subcontinent as slaves by the Portuguese and Arab merchants.<ref name=\"Prashad\">{{Citation | title=Everybody Was Kung Fu Fighting: Afro-Asian Connections and the Myth of Cultural Purity | author=Vijay Prashad | year=2002 | publisher=Beacon Press | isbn=0-8070-5011-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xiO6zUS9gigC | quote=... since the captains of the African and Arab vessels bore the title Sidi (from Sayyid, or the lineage of Muhammad), the African settlers on the Indian mainland came to be called Siddis ...}}</ref> Siddis are primarily [[Sufism|Sufi Muslims]], although some are [[Hindu]]s and others [[Roman Catholic]] Christians.<ref name=\"ali1996j\">{{Citation | title=The African dispersal in the Deccan | author=Shanti Sadiq Ali | year=1996 | publisher=Orient Blackswan | isbn=81-250-0485-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-3CPc22nMqIC | quote=... Among the Siddi families in Karnataka there are Catholics, Hindus and Muslims ... It was a normal procedure for the Portuguese to baptise African slaves ... After living for generations among Hindus they considered themselves to be Hindus ... The Siddi Hindus owe allegiance to Saudmath ...}}</ref> [[Malik Ambar]], a prominent military figure in Indian history at large, remains a figure of veneration to the Siddis of Gujarat.\n\n==Bharuchi and Surti Muslims==\nThere is historical evidence of Arabs and Persians settling along the [[Konkan]]-Gujarat coast as early as the 9th, 8th and perhaps 7th century.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wink|first=Andr\u00e9|title=Al-Hind, the making of the Indo-Islamic world|year=1990|publisher=E.J. Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9004092498|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U7Q3AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA68&dq=arabs,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=arabs%2C%20gujarat&f=false|edition=2. ed., amended.|accessdate=29 January 2014|quote=Up to about the tenth century the largest settlement of Arabs and Persian Muslim traders are not found in Malabar however but rather more to the north in coastal towns of the Konkan and Gujarat, where in pre-Islamic times the Persians dominated the trade with the west. Here the main impetus to Muslim settlement came from the merchants of the Persian Gulf and Oman, with a minority from Hadramaut.}}</ref> Arab traders landed at [[Ghogha]] (located just across the narrow Gulf of [[Cambay]] from [[Bharuch]]/[[Surat]]) around the early seventh century and built a masjid there facing [[Jeruselum]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Schimmel|first=Annemarie|title=Handbuch der Orientalistik.|year=1980|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9004061177|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TYImm1TnemwC&pg=PA65&dq=arabs,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=arabs%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> Thus Gujarat has the oldest mosque in India built between 624-626 C.E. by the Arabs who traded and stayed there. These Arabs and others who settled in [[Bharuch]] and [[Surat]] were sailors, merchants and [[nakhuda]]s, who belonged to various [[South Arabia]]n coastal tribes while others were from the [[Persian Gulf]] and [[Mediterranean]], and large numbers married local women adopting the local Gujarati language and customs over time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dunn|first1=Ross E.|title=The adventures of Ibn Battuta, a Muslim traveler of the fourteenth century|date=2005|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0-520-24385-4|edition=Rev. ed. with a new pref.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Js8qHFVw2gEC&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Many of these \"foreign merchants\" were transient visitors, men of South Arabian and Persian Gulf ports, who migrated in and out of Cambay with the rhythm of the monsoons. But others were men with Persian and fewer Arab patronyms whose families had settled in the town generations, even centuries earlier, intermarrying with Konkani ethnic origins within Gujarats women, and assimilating everyday customs of the Hindu hinterland}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Boyajian|first1=James C.|title=Portuguese trade in Asia under the Habsburgs, 1580-1640|date=2008|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore, Md.|isbn=978-0-8018-8754-3|page=71|edition=Pbk.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=C0lrDYYzMyAC&pg=PA71&dq=gujarat+egypt+trade#v=onepage&q=gujarat%20egypt%20trade&f=false|accessdate=20 February 2015|quote=The history of Indian Ocean trade is a succession of alien merchant diasporas establishing themselves and eventually dominating the region. Gujarat's Muslim community, for example, had originated from traders their mosques, and later the very small settlements of merchants from Turkey, Egypt, Persia and Arabia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Rai|first1=edited by Rajesh|last2=Reeves|first2=Peter|title=The South Asian diaspora transnational networks and changing identities|date=2009|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0-203-89235-0|page=33|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bwJD2WBNtNMC&pg=PA33&dq=gujarat%27s+muslims+egypt#v=onepage&q=gujarat's%20muslims%20egypt&f=false|accessdate=20 February 2015|quote=The social world of the Muslim merchants was complex. The heterogeneity of the Muslim merchant community was made up by the trade but much smaller number of settlers originating from various countries,  as well as by those who were peripatetic traders, coming from places like Persia, Egypt and few from Afghanistan.}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of history, a number of famous Arab travelers, scholars, Sufi-saints and geographers who visited India, have described the presence of thriving Arab-Muslim communities scattered along the Konkan-Gujarat coast.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ashish Vashi & Harit Mehta|title=Gujarat built mosques to draw Arab ships|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Gujarat-built-mosques-to-draw-Arab-ships/articleshow/5582255.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=14 February 2015|quote=The accounts of Arab travellers like Masudi, Istakhari, Ibn Hauqal and others, who visited Gujarat between the 9th and 12th centuries, amply testify to the settlements of Muslims in Cambay and other cities of Gujarat.}}</ref> Suleiman of Basra who reached [[Thana, Maharashtra|Thana]] in 841 AD, observed that the [[Rashtrakuta]] empire which extended from [[Bharuch]] to Chaul during his time, was on friendly terms with the Arabs, and Balhara kings appointed Arab merchant princes as governors and administrators in their vast kingdom.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Acyuta Y\u0101j\u00f1ika, Suchitra Sheth|title=The shaping of modern Gujarat : plurality, Hindutva, and beyond|date=2005|publisher=Penguin Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=0-14400-038-5|page=42|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wmKIiAPgnF0C&pg=PA42&dq=siraf,+gujarat,+persia#v=onepage&q=siraf%2C%20gujarat%2C%20persia&f=false|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ipgrave|first1=Michael|last2=editors|first2=David Marshall|title=Humanity : texts and contexts : Christian and Muslim perspectives : a record of the sixth Building Bridges seminar convened by the Archbishop of Canterbury, National University of Singapore, December 2007|date=2010|publisher=Georgetown University Press|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=978-1-58901-716-0|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/?id=csDpA4gnp-4C&pg=PA40&dq=tajiks,+gujarat+sultanate#v=onepage&q=tajiks%2C%20gujarat%20sultanate&f=false|accessdate=22 February 2015|quote=Memorials can be found in Gujarat honoring Arab Muslims who martyred themselves fighting against Muslim Turks on behalf of Hindu kingdoms. These same kingdoms endowed mosques on behalf of Arab traders.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-link=John Hinnells|editor2-link=Alan Williams|title=Parsis in India and the Diaspora|date=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134067527|pages=51, 52|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ywV9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=sanjan,+madhumati#v=onepage&q=sanjan%2C%20madhumati&f=false|accessdate=29 March 2015|quote=The Chinchani copper plates, datable to the early 10th century,  mention the appointment of Muhammed Sugapita (Sanskrit - 'Madhumati'), a Tajik, as governor of 'Sanyanapattana' (Sanjan port) by the Rashtrakuta king from 878 to 915 AC (Sircar 1962)... This fact is relevant in that it mentions a Muslim administrator controlling the region during the late 9th, and early 10th century... That Sanjan had a large and cosmopolitan population is mentioned in the accounts of travelers as well as the Indian inscriptions and grants mentioned above. While the local tribal populations consisted largely of Kolis and Mahars, the inscriptions list Muslims and Arabs, Panchagaudiya Brahmins, Modha Baniyas and Zoroastrians (Sankalia 1983: 210)}}</ref> [[Ibn Hawqal]], a 10th-century Muslim Arab geographer and chronicler while on his travels observed that mosques flourished in four cities of Gujarat that had Hindu kings, with mosques being found in Cambay, [[Kutch]], Saymur and [[Patan district|Patan]], alluding to an atmosphere where Muslim foreigners were assimilated into the local milieu of medieval Gujarati societies.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wink|first1=Andr\u00e9|title=Al-Hind, the making of the Indo-Islamic world|date=1990|publisher=E.J. Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=90-04-09249-8|page=178|edition=2. ed., amended.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bCVyhH5VDjAC&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=mosques,+in+cambay,+patan,+chaul#v=onepage&q=mosques%2C%20in%20cambay%2C%20patan%2C%20chaul&f=false|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Pearson|first1=M. N.|title=Merchants and rulers in Gujarat : the response to the Portuguese in the sixteenth century|date=1976|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0-520-02809-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/merchantsrulersi0000pear/page/25 25]|url=https://archive.org/details/merchantsrulersi0000pear|url-access=registration|accessdate=14 February 2015|quote=Most of these \"foreign\" Muslims were resident in Gujarat, with their own houses there, and so were in fact subjects of Gujarat, whatever their country of birth, which could be Turkey, Egypt, Arabia or Persia. The heterogeneity of the Muslim population was not confined to merchants, for the sultans made a practice of tempting capable foreigners to Gujarat with handsome salaries, to serve in their armies.}}</ref> His well-known Iranian contemporary [[Estakhri]], the Persian medieval geographer who traveled to Cambay and other regions of Gujarat during the same period, echoed the words spoken by his predecessors alongside his itineraries.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Satish Chandra Misra|title=Muslim Communities in Gujarat: Preliminary Studies in Their History and Social Organization|date=1964|publisher=Asia Publishing House|page=5|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f_AdAAAAMAAJ&q=istakhri,+gujarat&dq=istakhri,+gujarat|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> [[Al-Masudi]], an Arab historian from [[Baghdad]] who was a descendant of [[Abdullah ibn Masud|Abdullah Ibn Mas'ud]], a companion of [[Muhammad]] traveled to Gujarat in 918 C.E, and bore written witness account that more than 10,000 Arab Muslims from [[Siraf]] (Persia) [[Madha]] in Oman, Hadhramaut in [[Yemen]], [[Basra]], Baghdad, and other cities in the Middle East, had settled in the seaport of Chamoor, a port close to [[Bharuch]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Shaykh Gibril Fouad Haddad|title=Abul Hasan Ali Al-Masudi|url=http://sunnah.org/wordpress/2008/07/18/abul-hasan-ali-al-masudi/|website=As-Sunnah Foundation of America|accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cunha|first1=J. Gerson Da|title=Notes on the history and antiquities of Chaul and Bassein|date=1993|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=New Delhi|isbn=8120608453|page=8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xOPlusO8qcAC&pg=PA8&dq=al+masudi,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=al%20masudi%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=23 February 2015|quote=The Lar, also called Lardesa, mentioned by Masudi, is evidently the territory of Gujarat and the Northern Konkan, embracing Broach, Thana, and Chaul, and which name is given by Ptolemy as Larike...As regards Balhara, whom Masudi mentions as the reigning prince to whom Saimur was tributary, it has long been identified as the name of the dynasty which reigned at Valabhi (Valabhipura) in Gujarat, and according to Soliman, a merchant and one of the greatest travellers of his age, was in his time the chief of all the greatest princes in India, the latter acknowledging his preeminence; while the Arabs themselves were shown great favours and enjoyed great privileges in his dominions.}}</ref>\n\nDespite the medieval conquest of Gujarat by [[Alauddin Khalji]] and its annexation to the [[Delhi Sultanate]] in the 13th century, peaceful Islamic settlements appear to have continued under Hindu rule. Bi-lingual Indian inscriptions from [[Somnath]] in Sanskrit and Arabic, make reference to the Arab and Iranian shipowners who constructed mosques in Gujarat from the grants given to Muslims by the [[Vaghela dynasty|Vaghela]] rajput ruler, Arjunadeva.\n<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ray|first1=edited by Bharati|title=Different types of history|date=2009|publisher=Pearson Longman|location=Delhi|isbn=978-8131718186|page=43|edition=1. impr.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NmZzDUYNb0AC&pg=PA43&dq=Arjunadeva,+Gujarat,+grant,#v=onepage&q=Arjunadeva%2C%20Gujarat%2C%20grant%2C&f=false|quote=The person responsible for the construction of the mosque was a sailor and shipowner known as Firuz b. Abu Ibrahim from the state of Hormuz, and in the Arabic version the Muslim ruler to whom these sailors gave their allegiance is recorded as Abu Nusrat Mamud b. Ahmad.... Firuz the shipwner is not the only Persian who appears to have been a person of some standing among the Muslim communities of Gujarat. In Bhadresvar one of the tombstones belongs to one Abu'l-faraj b. Ali, from Siraf, at that time one of the most important ports on the Iranian coast of the Persian Gulf. Another inscription found in Cambay, records the construction of a mosque by Ali b. Shapur in 615/1218-19. The name Shapur shows the Iranian origin of this personage. Other epitaphs are to be found in Cambay belonging to Abi'l-mahasin b. Ardeshir al-Ahwi (d.630/1232-3), Sharaf al-din Murtida b. Mohammad al-Istarabadi, and Ali b Salar b. Ali Yazdi... In the inscription of the mosque at Junagadh, Iraj, the name of a southern Iranian city, near Ramhurmuz, or of the ancestor of Abulqasim b. Ali is also an indication of the Iranian origin of our \"chief of the marchants and shipmasters of the town\". }}</ref> Similar epitaphs mention the arrival of pious Muslim nakhudas from [[Hormuz, Fars|Hormuz]] as well as families from [[Bam, Iran|Bam]] residing in Cambay, and from the discovery of tombstones of personages from [[Siraf]], at the time one of the most important ports on the Iranian coast in the Persian Gulf, suggests altogether that the Muslim community of [[Junagadh]] had a strong and established link with [[Iran]] through the commercial sea routes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bayani-Wolpert|first1=Mehrdad Shokoohy with contributions by Manijeh|last2=Shokoohy|first2=Natalie H.|title=Bhadre\u015bvar ; the oldest Islamic monuments in India|date=1988|publisher=E.J. Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9004083413|page=43|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NmZzDUYNb0AC&pg=PA43&dq=persian+muslims,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=persian%20muslims%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref> The 19th century ''European Gazetteer'' by George Newenham Wright,  corroborates this cultural exchange through the ages as he points out that the Arab inhabitants of [[Mukalla]], capital city of the [[Hadhramaut]] coastal region in [[Yemen]], were known to intermarry with the Mohammedans of [[Kathiawar]] and those resident from other areas of Gujarat.<ref>{{cite book|author1=George Newenham Wright|title=A New and Comprehensive Gazetteer, Volume 5|page=41|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sSQDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA41&dq=Bab-al-Makkah,+surat+gujarat#v=onepage&q=Bab-al-Makkah%2C%20surat%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=The coast of Southern Arabia, was explored in 1833, by Mr. Bird. The people at Mukallah intermarry with the Mohammedans of Katehwar and Gujarat. The sheikh's youngest wife is the daughter of a petty chief in that quarter. The town has rather an imposing appearance as approaching it from the sea.|year=1838}}</ref>\n\nArabic sources speak of the warm reception of the significant immigration of [[Hadhrami people|Hadhrami]] ''s\u0101da'' (descendants of [[Muhammed]]) who settled in [[Surat]] during the [[Gujarat Sultanate]]. Prominent and well respected [[Sayyid|S\u0101da]] who claimed noble descent through [[Abu Bakr al-Aydarus]] (\"Patron Saint of Aden\"),<ref>Jos\u00e9-Marie Bel, Th\u00e9odore Monod, ''Aden: Port mythique du Y\u00e9men'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=TURek_n2BrkC&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=aidrus+aden+mosque+saint&source=bl&ots=ONzOZ0--id&sig=r9xheL_PhnPLydaPdgqBd-hVd-c&hl=en&ei=sd7JSZahNJCo6gOWkOC6Ag&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=7&ct=result pg 99]</ref> were held in high esteem among the people and became established as Arab religious leaderships of local Muslims. Intermarriages with Indian Muslim women were highly sought<ref>{{cite book|first1=ed. by Ulrike Freitag|last1=Ulrike Freitag, William G. Clarence-Smith|title=Hadhrami traders, scholars and statesmen in the Indian Ocean : 1750s - 1960s|date=1997|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden [u.a.]|isbn=9789004107717|page=67|edition=illustrated|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gBTbS4eNGp8C&pg=PA67&dq=surat,+gujarat,+Islam,+muslim,+arab#v=onepage&q=surat%2C%20gujarat%2C%20Islam%2C%20muslim%2C%20arab&f=false|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref> which led to a [[creole peoples|creole]] Hadhrami-Indian community to flourish in Gujarat by the 17th century.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ho|first1=Engseng|title=The graves of Tarim genealogy and mobility across the Indian Ocean|date=2006|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520938694|page=167|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YMcZU0VHdG0C&pg=PA167&lpg=PA167&dq=arabic+sources,+hadhrami,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=arabic%20sources%2C%20hadhrami%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nEarly 14th-century [[Maghrebi]] adventurer, [[Ibn Batuta]], who visited India with his entourage, recalls in his memoirs about Cambay, one of the great emporia of the Indian Ocean that indeed:<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunn|first=Ross E.|title=The adventures of Ibn Battuta, a Muslim traveler of the fourteenth century|year=1986|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520057715|page=218|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZF2spo9BKacC&pg=PA218&dq=gujaratis,+maldives#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20maldives&f=false|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote| [[Cambay]] is one of the most beautiful cities as regards the artistic architecture of its houses and the construction of its mosques. The reason is that the majority of its inhabitants are foreign merchants, who continually build their beautiful houses and wonderful mosques - an achievement in which they endeavor to surpass each other.}}\n\nIn the 17th century, the eminent city of Surat, famous for its cargo export of silk and [[diamonds]] had come on a par with contemporary [[Venice]] and [[Beijing]] which were some of the great mercantile cities of Europe and Asia,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Poros|first1=Maritsa V.|title=Modern migrations : Gujarati Indian networks in New York and London|date=2011|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Stanford, Calif.|isbn=978-0-8047-7222-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_tm_n7uSXT8C&pg=PT30&lpg=PT30&dq=surat,+venice+and+beijing#v=onepage&q=surat%2C%20venice%20and%20beijing&f=false|accessdate=16 February 2015|quote=Indeed, Fernand Braudel likened Surat to some of the great mercantile cities of Europe and Asia, such as Venice and Beijing.... Godinho estimated that Surat's population was more than 100,000, but less with some settlements of people from other cities all over from India residing in the city as well as some foreigners frequenting it for business. He even claimed that it surpasses our \"Evora in grandeur\"}}</ref> and earned the distinguished title, ''Bab al-Makkah'' (Gate of Mecca)because it is one of the great places of the subcontinent where ancient Hindus welcomed Islam and it flourished as time went on.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David Smith|title=Hinduism and modernity|date=2003|publisher=Blackwell|location=Oxford|isbn=0-631-20862-3|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/?id=x-aRSuypah8C&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=Bab-al-Makkah,+surat+gujarat#v=onepage&q=Bab-al-Makkah%2C%20surat%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=Surat was then the place of embarkation of pilgrims to Mecca; known as Bab al-Makkah or  the Gate of Mecca, it was almost a sacred place for the Muslims of India. More to the point it was the main city for foreign imports, where many merchants had their bases,  and all the European trading companies were established. Its population was more than 100, 000.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The journal of Asian studies, Volume 35, Issues 1-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lJtRAQAAIAAJ&q=Bab-al-Makkah,+surat+gujarat&dq=Bab-al-Makkah,+surat+gujarat|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=For a pious emperor, Surat had more than economic and political importance; it was the port from which the hajj (pilgrimage) ships left Mughal India for the Red Sea. The port was variously known as Bab-al-Makkah, the Bab-ul-Hajj, the Dar-al-Hajj, and the Bandar-i-Mubarak.|year = 1975}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Gujarati Muslims ==\n\nMufti Abdur Rahman Ibn Yusuf Mangera of the UK who is a prominent Islamic Scholar once listed as one of the 500 most influential Muslims in the world, Mufti Ismail Ibn Musa Menk, another prominent Islamic Scholar also of Gujarati descent, South African cricketer [[Hashim Amla]], South African Quran - Bible Scholar [[Ahmed Deedat]], Carabbean eschatologist and Islamic scholar [[Imran N. Hosein]], [[Badruddin Tyabji]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Britain: Discover how South Asians shaped the nation, 1870-1950|url=http://www.open.ac.uk/researchprojects/makingbritain/content/badruddin-tyabji|website=The Open University|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Badruddin Tyabji was the son of Cambay merchant, Tyab Ali, and his wife, Ameena, the daughter of a rich mullah, Meher Ali.}}</ref> a Congress president and [[Mohammad Ali Jinnah]], the founding father of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jinnah didn't know Urdu, was fluent in Gujarati|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Jinnah-didnt-know-Urdu-was-fluent-in-Gujarati/articleshow/4950044.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=But Jinnah was fluent in Gujarati. He could read as well as write Gujarati, his mother tongue. Jinnah was a native of Paneli \u2014 not far from Gandhiji's birthplace Porbandar. It is often said the issue of Partition boiled down to these two Kathiawadis.}}</ref> Bollywood is represented by [[Asha Parekh]] who is half Gujarati Muslim, [[Farooq Shaikh]], and [[Sanjeeda Sheikh]]. Famous Indian film score composers include [[Salim-Sulaiman]] Merchant who are [[Ismaili]] [[Shia]] and [[Taher Saifuddin]], who was the 51st [[Da'i al-Mutlaq]] of the [[Dawoodi Bohras]], a sect within [[Shia Islam]]. Famous political activists such as [[Ahmed Timol]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/ahmed-timol |title=Ahmed Timol &#124; South African History Online |publisher=Sahistory.org.za |date= |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> [[Yusuf Dadoo]], and [[Ahmed Kathrada]] played a leading role in the [[anti-apartheid movement]] of South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=34455|title=Review of Kathrada, A. M., No Bread for Mandela: Memoirs of Ahmed Kathrada, Prisoner No. 468/64|first=Antoinette|last=Burton|authorlink=Antoinette Burton|date=1 May 2012|website=www.h-net.org}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sayyid of Gujarat]]\n* [[Khoja]]\n* [[Memon people|Memon]]\n* [[Ismailis]]\n* [[Alavi Bohras]]\n* [[Dawoodi Bohras]]\n*[[Memons (Kathiawar)|Khatiawari Memon]]\n* [[Muslim Rajputs]]\n* [[Islam in India]]\n* [[Gujarat Sultanate]]\n* [[Nakhuda]]\n* [[Jats of Kutch]]\n* [[Pathans of Gujarat]]\n* [[Arabs in India]]\n* [[Al Masudi]]\n* [[Ibn Batuta]]\n* [[Nuruddin ar-Raniri]] from [[Rander]]\n* [[Abu Bakr al-Aydarus]], [[Hadhrami people|Hadhrami]] religious scholar of [[sufism]]\n* [[Ba 'Alawi sada]]\n* [[Abdullah ibn Alawi al-Haddad]]\n* [[Shah e Alam]]\n* [[Wajihuddin Alvi]]\n* [[List of ziyarat locations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Indian Muslim}}\n\n[[Category:Islam in India by location]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of India|*]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Muhajir communities]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of Gujarat|*]]\n[[Category:South African people of Gujarati descent|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious group\n|group = Gujarati Muslim\n|image = \n|caption = \n|population =  {{Circa|'''6.8 million'''|lk=yes}}{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n|region1 = {{flag|India}}\n|pop1    = 5,800,000 \n|ref1    = <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/Religion_PCA.html|title=Census of India Website : Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|website=www.censusindia.gov.in|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n| region2 = {{flag|Pakistan}}\n| pop2    = 1,000,000\n| ref2    = <ref name=e20>{{e20|guj}}</ref>\n|poptime = \n|popplace =  [[India]], [[Pakistan]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[South Africa]], [[Kenya]], [[Tanzania]], [[Uganda]], [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Madagascar]]\n|langs = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]],<ref name=omniglot>{{cite web|title=Gujar\u0101t\u012b|url=http://www.omniglot.com/writing/gujarati.htm|publisher=Onmiglot: online encyclopaedia of writing systems and languages|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> [[Urdu]]\n|rels=  [[Islam]]\n}}\n\nThe term '''Gujarati Muslims''' is usually used to signify an Indian [[Muslim]] from the state of [[Gujarat]] in western coast of India.  Gujarati Muslims are very prominent in industry and medium-sized businesses, and there is a very large Gujarati Muslim community in [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Patel|first1=edited by Sujata|last2=Masselos|first2=Jim|title=Bombay and Mumbai : the city in transition|date=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New Delhi|isbn=0195663179|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jmPuAAAAIAAJ&q=gujarati+muslims+in+mumbai&dq=gujarati+muslims+in+mumbai}}</ref>. Gujrati Muslim are termed as the richest Muslims in India and Pakistan as well. Many members of this community migrated to [[Pakistan]] in 1947 and have settled in [[Sindh]] province especially in [[Karachi]], contributing to the national welfare and economy of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Laurent Gayer|title=Karachi : ordered disorder and the struggle for the city|date=2014|isbn=978-0-19-935444-3|page=300|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BklRBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA300&dq=gujaratis,+memons,+pakistan#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20memons%2C%20pakistan&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=Out of Pakistan's forty-two largest industrial groups, thirty-six were in the hands of Karachi-based businessmen - generally members of the Gujarati/Kutchi/Kathiawari trading sects, both Sunni (Memon) and Shia (Khojas, Bohras, etc.)  Whereas they accounted for 0.4 per cent of Pakistan's total population, Gujarati trading groups (they are considered [[Muhajir people|Muhajir]] since many of their members were already settled in Karachi before the independence) controlled 43 per cent of the country's industrial capital. Halai Memons alone (0.3 per cent of the national population) owned 27 per cent of these industries. And while he patronised Pashtun entrepreneurs in Karachi, Ayub Khan also relied upon Gujarati businessmen to finance his electoral campaign in 1964, while facilitating the entry into politics of some Muhajir entrepreneurs, such as Sadiq Dawood, a Memon industrialist who became an MNA,  and the Treasurer of Ayub's Convention Muslim League.}}</ref> Having earned a formidable accolade as some of India's greatest seafaring merchants,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peck|first1=Amelia|title=Interwoven Globe: The Worldwide Textile Trade, 1500-1800|publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York|isbn=978-1-58839-496-5|page=15|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BYjh82N63IQC&pg=PA15&dq=gujarati+merchants,+red+sea#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20merchants%2C%20red%20sea&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Of the Asian trading communities the most successful were the Gujaratis, as witnessed not only by Pires and Barbosa but by a variety of other sources. All confirm that merchants from the Gujarati community routinely held the most senior post open to an expatriate trader, that of shah-bandar (controller of maritime trade).|year=2013}}</ref> the centuries-old Gujarati diaspora is found scattered throughout the ''Near East, Indian Ocean, and Southern Hemisphere'' regions everywhere in between Africa and Japan with a notable presence in:<ref>{{cite web|title=Where on earth do they speak Gujarati?|url=http://www.verbix.com/maps/language/Gujarati.html|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> [[Hong Kong]],<ref>{{cite book|authors=ed. by Robert Bickers|title=New frontiers : imperialism's new communities in East Asia, 1842-1953|date=2000|publisher=Manchester Univ. Press|location=Manchester [u.a.]|isbn=0-7190-5604-7|page=67|edition=1. publ.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OmW7AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA67&dq=gujarati+muslims,+hong+kong#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20muslims%2C%20hong%20kong&f=false|quote=The 1889 Hong Kong Directory and Hong List for the Far East lists three Sindhi firms in Hong Kong among a total of thirty-one firms, of which the majority were Parsi and Gujarati Muslim.}}</ref> [[United Kingdom|Britain]], [[Portugal]], [[R\u00e9union]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Nandita Dutta|title=An Indian Reunion|url=http://www.littleindia.com/life/12041-an-indian-reunion.html|website=littleindia.com|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Raziah Locate is a manager in a hospitality school. Her grandfather Omarjee Ismael embarked on a voyage with his wife in 1870 from Kathor, near Surat, in Gujarat. He came to Reunion Island to seek better opportunities to further his trade in clothing. Her grandfather was one of the 40,000 merchants, traders and artisans from Gujarat who are said to have voluntary migrated to Reunion Island starting in the 1850s. Her grandfather was one of the pioneers who paved the way for other Gujarati Muslims to settle in Reunion, who have built a mosque and a madrasa on the island.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716114621/http://www.littleindia.com/life/12041-an-indian-reunion.html|archive-date=16 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Oman]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Hugh Eakin|title=In the Heart of Mysterious Oman|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/aug/14/heart-mysterious-oman/|website=The New York Review of Books|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=August 14, 2014}}</ref> [[Yemen]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Nafeesa Syeed|title=Learning Gujarati in Yemen|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2012/09/24/learning-gujarati-in-yemen/|website=indiarealtime.com|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Mr. Haji, clad in the gold-trimmed, white cap that is standard for Bohra men, was in a flurry on a recent Friday, as he catered to streams of constituents and answered phone calls. He slid effortlessly between Arabic, Urdu, English and Dawat ni zabaan\u2014a strain of Gujarati particular to Bohras that is peppered with Arabic and Persian. He explained that they have other shrines in Yemen, but this is one of the most important. Some 10,000 Bohras, mostly from India but also from their populations in Pakistan, East Africa, the United States, Europe and the Middle East, travel here each year.}}</ref> [[Mozambique]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Nazar Abbas|title=Pakistanis who have never seen Pakistan|url=http://www.thefridaytimes.com/tft/pakistanis-who-have-never-seen-pakistan/|website=The Friday Times|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=After ties broke down between India and Portugal, Gujarati Muslims stranded in Mozambique were given Pakistani citizenship...Merchants from Diu had settled on the island of Mozambique in the early 1800s. Hindus from Diu, Sunni Muslims from Daman, and others from Goa migrated to Mozambique as small traders, construction workers and petty employees. Many Gujaratis moved from South Africa to Mozambique in the latter half of the 19th century.}}</ref> [[Zanzibar]],<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ababu Minda Yimene|title=An African Indian Community in Hyderabad: Siddi Identity, Its Maintenance and Change|date=2004|isbn=3-86537-206-6|pages=66, 67|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DigPvwHTqJ4C&pg=PA67&dq=gujaratis+in+england,+19th+century#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%20in%20england%2C%2019th%20century&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Some centuries later, the Gujarati merchants established permanent trading posts in Zanzibar, consolidating their influence in the Indian Ocean... Gujarati Muslims, and their Omani partners, engaged in a network of mercantile activities among Oman, Zanzibar and Bombay. Thanks to those mercantile Gujarati, India remained by far the principal trading partner of Zanzibar.}}</ref> [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Myanmar|Burma]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Dr Asghar Ali Engineer |title=Rohingya Muslims in Myanmar and recent riots - an Aman Report |url=http://www.csss-isla.com/arch-July-1-15-2012.htm |website=Centre for study of society and secularism |accessdate=9 February 2015 |quote=Lot of Muslims had gone from Surat and still there is a beautiful Surti mosque. Muslims in Myanmar are highly diverse. There are very few ethnic Burmese Muslims, most of them are migrants from different parts of India when Burma was a part of India. There are large number of Tamil, Gujarati and Bengali and Bohra Muslims and very few Urdu speaking Muslims since Urdu speaking are not in business. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209225842/http://www.csss-isla.com/arch-July-1-15-2012.htm |archivedate=February 9, 2015 }}</ref> [[Madagascar]],<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pedro Machado|title=Ocean of Trade|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-07026-4|page=232|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ODfJBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA232&lpg=PA232&dq=gujarati+muslims,+madagascar#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20muslims%2C%20madagascar&f=false|quote=Gujarati merchants may also have financed slave voyages to Madagascar in the nineteenth century. They sailed to its west coast from the mid 1810s to the mid 1820s but do not appear to have become extensively involved in this trafficking, either as shippers or as financiers. This is likely explained by the increasing presence in coastal Madagascar of Khoja and Bohra Shi'ia merchants from Kutch who, together with the Bhatiya merchants, established a significant presence there as financiers of the slave trade from the second decade of the nineteenth century.|date=2014-11-06}}</ref> [[South Africa]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Mauritius]], [[Pakistan]], [[Zambia]] and [[East Africa]] \n\nAccording to the 2011 [[Census of India]], the Gujarati Muslim population was 5,846,761 but significant numbers of Gujarati Muslims are found within the larger context of the Gujarati diaspora that became established throughout all the inhabited continents of the world.{{cn|date=July 2019}}\n\nMost Gujarati Muslims have Gujarati language as their mother tongue, but some communities such as the [[Momin Ansari]], [[Memons]],<ref>Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency, Gujarat Population: Musalmans and Parsis, Volume IX pages 13 to 14 Government Central Press, Bombay</ref> [[Gujarati Shaikh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unescoparzor.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=15&Itemid=60 |title=Parzor &#124; The UNESCO Parsi Zoroastrian Project |publisher=Unescoparzor.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref><ref name=\"survey\">People of India Gujarat Volume XXII Part One Editors R. B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan and M Azeez Mohideen pages 74 to 77</ref> and others, have [[Urdu]] as their mother tongue.<ref>name=\"Indian Census 2001 - Religion\" [http://demotemp257.nic.in/httpdoc/Census_Data_2001/Census_data_finder/C_Series/Population_by_religious_communities.htm Indian Census 2001 - Religion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312153215/http://demotemp257.nic.in/httpdoc/Census_Data_2001/Census_data_finder/C_Series/Population_by_religious_communities.htm |date=2007-03-12 }}</ref>\n\nThe majority of Gujarati Muslims are Sunni, with a minority of heterodox Shi'ite groups.\n\nThe Gujarati Muslims are further sub-divided into groups, such as the [[Sunni Bohra|Sunni Vohra/Bohra]], [[Ismailism|Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl\u012b]], [[Khoja]], [[Dawoodi Bohra]], [[Memons (Kathiawar)|Memon]], [[Surti Muslims|Surti]], [[Pathan people]], [[Soomra (Muslim)|Khatri]], [[Ghanchi (Muslim)|Ghanchi]] and [[Chhipa]] each with their own customs and traditions.\n\nGujarati Muslims played a pivotal role in establishing [[Islam]] in [[Southeast Asia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gujarat helped establish Islam in SE Asia|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/ampnbspGujarat-helped-establish-Islam-in-SE-Asia/articleshow/11262585.cms|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|last=Prabhune|first=Tushar|location=[[Ahmedabad]]|date=December 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nLocated in the westernmost portion of India, Gujarat includes the region of [[Kutch]], [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]], and the territories between the rivers [[Banas River|Banas]] and [[Daman Ganga River|Damanganga]]. [[Islam]] came early to Gujarat, with immigrant communities of [[Arab]] and [[Persian people|Persian]] traders.  Most came as traders as they did before Islam and built a masjid during the times of Muhammad and other parts of the western seacoast of India as early as the 8th century C.E, spreading Islam soon as the religion gained a foothold in the Arabian peninsula.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Gokhale|title=Surat In The Seventeenth Century|publisher=Popular Prakashan|page=28|url=https://books.google.com/?id=frbYo91TuV4C&pg=PA28&dq=surat,+gujarat,+Islam,+muslim,+arab#v=onepage&q=surat%2C%20gujarat%2C%20Islam%2C%20muslim%2C%20arab&f=false|accessdate=23 February 2015|quote=Islam was introduced into Gujarat in the 7th century C.E. The first Arab raid came in 635 when the Governor of Bahrain sent an expedition against Broach. Then through the centuries colonies of Arab and Persian merchants began sprouting in the port cities of  Gujarat, such as Cambay, Broach and Surat.|isbn=9788171542208}}</ref> They were later joined by [[Persian people|Persian]] traders from [[Greater Iran]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mallison|first1=edited by Tazim R. Kassam, Fran\u00e7oise|title=Gin\u0101ns : texts and contexts : essays on Ismaili hymns from South Asia in honour of Zawahir Moir|date=2010|publisher=Primus Books|location=Delhi|isbn=978-8190891875|page=150|edition=Rev.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xmh3gQjPHkAC&pg=PA150&dq=PERSIAN+merchants,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=PERSIAN%20merchants%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=28 April 2015|quote=In the early period, it appears that the Ismailis in western India, consisted of ethnic Arab or Persian merchant settlers, as well as local converts from pastoralist, cultivating or merchant groups. They may have included militarised peasants and pastoralists from north-west India, some of whom went on to become part of the emerging Rajput status hierarchy... After the fall of Alamut to the Mongols in 1256, more Nizari missionaries came to Sind and Gujarat, Ucch in particular becoming an important centre.}}</ref> Many of these early merchants were [[Ismaili]] [[Shia]], both [[Mustaali]] and [[Nizari]]. They laid the foundation of the [[Mustaali|Bohra]] and [[Khoja]] communities. In the early era however Gujarat was ruled by the [[Valabhi]] dynasty. In the thirteenth century, the last [[Hindu]] ruler Karna, was defeated by [[Alauddin Khalji]], the [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] [[Delhi Sultanate|Sultan of Dehli]]. This episode ushered a period of five centuries of Muslim Turkic and [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] rule, leading to a conversion of a number of Hindu Gujarati people to [[Islam]], and the creation of new communities such as the [[Molesalam Rajput|Molesalam]] and [[Miyana (community)|Miyana]] communities.\n\nIn the sixteenth century, the [[Memon people|Memon]] community immigrated from [[Sindh]] and settled in Kutch and [[Kathiawar]]. While in [[Bharuch]] and [[Surat]], a [[Schism (religion)|schism]] occurred among the Bohras, and a new community of [[Sunni Bohra]]s was created. Another Muslim sect, the [[Mahdawi]] also settled in Gujarat, and led to the creation of the [[Tai (caste)|Tai]] community.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berkeley|first1=Ira M. Lapidus, University of California|title=A history of Islamic societies|date=2014|isbn=978-0521514309|page=399|edition=Third|quote=The Mahdawi movement was important in Gujarat in the sixteenth century and was widely accepted during the reign of Sultan Akbar by the administrative, military, landowning, and merchant elites.}}</ref> In 1593, the Mughal Emperor [[Akbar]] conquered Gujarat, and incorporated Gujarat in the Mughal Empire. This period led to the settlement of the [[Mughal (tribe)|Mughal]] community. A good many [[Sayyid of Gujarat|Sayyid]] and [[Gujarati Shaikh|Shaikh]] families also are said to have arrived during the period of Mughal rule. With the establishment of the Sufi [[Suhrawardiyya|Suhrawardi]] and [[Chishti]] orders in [[Multan]], Sind and Gujarat, [[pir (Sufism)|pirs]] enjoyed state patronage.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berkeley|first1=Ira M. Lapidus, University of California|title=A history of Islamic societies|date=2014|isbn=978-0521514309|page=399|edition=Third|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kFJNBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA399&dq=PERSIAN+merchants,+Islam,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=PERSIAN%20merchants%2C%20Islam%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> At the same time, the Muslims from various provinces such as [[Hyderabad Deccan]], [[Kerala]], Balochistan, Sindh, [[Punjab]], Gujarat, [[Kashmir]] and other parts of South Asia also moved to capitals of Muslim empire in [[Delhi]] and [[Agra]]. After the death of the Mughal emperor [[Aurangzeb]], in 1707, Mughal rule began weaken after ruling for a century. Most of Gujarat fell to the [[Maratha]]s, and this period saw the dispersal of further Pathans and Baluchis, who came as mercenaries and were destroyed or defeated by the [[Maratha]]s. Gujarat fell to [[United Kingdom|British]] in the late 19th century.<ref name=\"Muslim Peoples pages 294\">Muslim Peoples: A World Ethnographic Survey editor Richard V Weekes pages 294 to 297</ref>\n\nGujarati Muslim merchants played an historically important role in facilitating the Portuguese discovery of \"[[Indies|the East Indies]]\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Gujarati showed Vasco 'da' way|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-03/ahmedabad/28223775_1_gama-vasco-da-gujarati|publisher=The Times of India|accessdate=1 October 2013|date=Oct 3, 2010|quote=Historians have differed over the identity of the sailor, calling him a Christian, a Muslim and a Gujarati. According to another account, he was the famous Arab navigator Ibn Majid. Some historians suggest Majid could not have been near the vicinity at the time. German author Justus says it was Malam who accompanied Vasco...Italian researcher Sinthia Salvadori too has concluded that it was Malam who showed Gama the way to India. Salvadori has made this observation in her 'We Came In Dhows', an account written after interacting with people in Gujarat.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Homage to a Historian: A Festschrift|year=1976|publisher=Dr. N. Subrahmanian 60th Birthday Celebration Committee|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CbgBAAAAMAAJ&q=Kanji+Malam&dq=Kanji+Malam|authors=N. Subrahmanian, Tamil\u0332an\u0332pan\u0332, S. Jeyapragasam|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Rethinking solidarity in global society : the challenge of globalisation for social and solidarity movements : 50 years after Bandung Asian-African Conference 1955|year=2007|publisher=Strategic Information and Research Development Centre|location=Petaling Jaya, Selangor, Malaysia|isbn=9789833782130|page=35|url=https://books.google.com/?id=R6zZAAAAMAAJ&q=Kanji+Malam&dq=Kanji+Malam|author=Darwis Khudori|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref> in spreading and propagating Islam to the [[Far East]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Aritonang|first1=edited by Jan Sihar|last2=Steenbrink|first2=Karel|title=A history of Christianity in Indonesia|date=2008|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=978-90-04-17026-1|page=11|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cUoGJSs9yOUC&pg=PA11&dq=gujarati+muslims,+indonesia#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20muslims%2C%20indonesia&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=The predominant Muslim position in the international trade was also represented by Muslim outposts along the southern coast of the Indian subcontinent. They included Randir, Surat and Cambay (in Gujarat). In fact, they had been supposed to have not only played a significant role in international Muslim trade, but also in the spread of Islam, in supposedly in the Malay-Indonesian archipelago.}}</ref> and in promoting the British [[Exploration of Africa|discovery of Africa]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Achyut Yagnik, Suchitra Sheth|title=The shaping of modern Gujarat : plurality, Hindutva, and beyond|date=2005|publisher=Penguin Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=0-14400-038-5|page=25|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wmKIiAPgnF0C&pg=PA25&dq=gujaratis,+memons,+pakistan#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20memons%2C%20pakistan&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=After the opening up of East Africa in the nineteenth century, they became pioneers of trading activity there, dominating not only the financial world but also the political affairs of the region. Interestingly, it was these Gujarati Muslim traders along with Kutchi Bhatias who provided equipment, rations and financial services to European explorers such as, Stanley,  Livingstone, Burton and Cameron, and thus facilitated the 'discovery of Africa'}}</ref> In Southeast Asia, Malays referred to the Islamic elite among them by the noble title of adhirajas.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hall|first1=Kenneth R.|title=A History of Early Southeast Asia Maritime Trade and Societal Development, 100-1500.|date=2010|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Pub. Group|location=Lanham|isbn=978-0742567627|page=309|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fjsEn3w4TPgC&pg=PA309&dq=Persian+traders,+Muslims,+Gujarat#v=onepage&q=Persian%20traders%2C%20Muslims%2C%20Gujarat&f=false|accessdate=28 April 2015|quote=All the Gujarati merchants were Muslims, and the elite among them were termed adhiraja, a Malay title of nobility, seemingly as an acknowledgment that there was a local mix of the resident Gujarati merchant elite and the Malay political aristocracy.}}</ref> The [[Sufi]] trader, [[Nuruddin ar-Raniri|Shaikh Randeri]] (Shaikh Raneri) was responsible for spreading Islam to [[Acheh]] in [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Biographical Encyclopaedia of Sufis: South Asia |author=N. Hanif |publisher=Sarup & Sons |year=2000 |isbn=9788176250870 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=O3GXOqPa67MC&pg=PA326&lpg=PA326&dq=shaikh+raniri#v=onepage&q=shaikh%20raniri&f=false }}</ref> \nSurti merchants in particular also pioneered the use of scientific concepts, and invented structural and mechanical advances in technology for the nationbuilding of [[Mauritius]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Dukhira|first=Chit|title=The genuis<!-- sic -->: Amode Ibrahim Atchia, (1868-1947)|url=http://www.lexpress.mu/article/genuis-amode-ibrahim-atchia-1868-1947|publisher=lexpess.mu.online}}</ref> such as introducing [[hydro-electric power]] to the people of [[Mauritius]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Atchia|first=Dr. Michael|title=Major Atchia, a model of enterprise|url=http://www.lexpress.mu/article/%E2%80%9Cmajor%E2%80%9D-atchia-model-enterprise|publisher=lexpress.mu.online}}</ref>\n\n== Jamat Bandi ==\nGujarati speaking Muslim society has a unique custom known as '''Jamat Bandi''', literally meaning communal solidarity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Muslim communities of Gujarat|url=http://twocircles.net/2011may03/muslim_communities_gujarat.html#.VNjCr-asUbA|website=TwoCircles.net|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Muslims of Gujarat are probably the most diverse of Muslim population of any other Indian state. Some of them came from different parts of the Islamic world over a period of thousand years to seek security, employment, trade, and to spread Islam; bringing with them their culture, knowledge, and their own versions of Islam. Though there has been much interaction with different Muslim groups, the differences have survived to make Gujarati Muslims a very diverse ummah...First came the Arabs; within the first 100 years of revelation of Quran, there were a number of Muslim towns along the coast of Gujarat. They were followed by Iranians, Africans, and Central Asians. Earlier Muslims came as traders; some came with the invading armies and settled down. Many others came seeking better employment opportunities, while some like Bohras came here fleeing persecution.}}</ref> This system is the traditional expression of communal solidarity. It is designed to regulate the affairs of the community and apply sanctions against infractions of the communal code. Almost all the main Gujarat communities, such as the [[Ismailism|Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl\u012b]],    [[Khoja]], [[Dawoodi Bohra]], [[Chhipa]], and [[Sunni Bohra]] have [[caste]] associations, known as jamats. Social organization at the Jamat Bandi level varies from community to community. In some communities, the Jamat simply runs a mosque and attached rest house, and a [[madrasah]]. Some larger communities, such as the [[Khoja]] and [[Memon people|Memon]] have developed elaborate and highly formalized systems with written and registered constitutions. Their organizations own large properties, undertake housing projects and schools, dispensaries and weekly newspapers.\n\n== Communities ==\nThe region of Kutch has always been historically distinct, with the Muslims there accounting for about twenty percent of the population. This region is characterised by salt deserts, such as the [[Rann of Kutch]]. Because of this landscape, the Kutch Muslims are [[Maldhari]] pastoral nomads found in the [[Banni Grasslands Reserve|Banni]] region of Kutch. Most of them are said to have originated in Sindh, and speak a dialect of [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] which has many [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] loanwords. Major [[Maldhari]] communities include the [[Sandhai Muslims]], [[Jats of Kutch|Jats]], [[Halaypotra]], [[Hingora]], [[Hingorja]], [[Junejo|Juneja]] and [[Samma (tribe)|Samma]] tribes.<ref>People of India Gujarat Volume XXI  Part  Two edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 487-491</ref> The other important Muslim community is the [[Memons (Kathiawar)|Khatiawari Memon]] community, that migrated and resettled beyond Gujarat state during partition of India in 1947.<ref>{{Citation|title=Memon people|date=2020-02-23|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Memon_people&oldid=942253688|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Khatiawari memon community is regarded as the wealthiest community in India and Pakistan. Mainly, due to their involvement in international trade and contribution to nations economy. [[Memons (Kathiawar)|Khatiawari memons]] are famous for their humanitarian services and other welfare services under the banner of [https://wmoworld.com/ World Memon Organization]. Khatiawari memons follow are also further divided under various surnames like Adamjee, Adani, Admani, Bagha, Bandukra, Chamadia, Dhedhi, Lakhani, Patel; [[Memons (Kathiawar)|Khatiawari memons]] proudly recall their rich history from their ansestral villages named [[Kutiyana]], [[Bantva]], [[Porbandar]] currently located in modern state of [[Gujarat]], [[India]].  \n\nThe Gujarat coastline is also home to significant numbers of [[Siddi]], otherwise known as ''Zanji'' or ''Habshi'', descendants of Africans e.g. [http://britishlibrary.typepad.co.uk/asian-and-african/2013/04/ikhlas-khan-the-african-prime-minister-of-bijapur.html Royal Habshis] (Abyssinian aristocracy e.g. [[Sidi Saiyyed Mosque|Siddi Sayyid]]), or [[Bantu peoples]] from Southeast Africa that were brought to the Indian subcontinent as slaves by the Portuguese and Arab merchants.<ref name=\"Prashad\">{{Citation | title=Everybody Was Kung Fu Fighting: Afro-Asian Connections and the Myth of Cultural Purity | author=Vijay Prashad | year=2002 | publisher=Beacon Press | isbn=0-8070-5011-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xiO6zUS9gigC | quote=... since the captains of the African and Arab vessels bore the title Sidi (from Sayyid, or the lineage of Muhammad), the African settlers on the Indian mainland came to be called Siddis ...}}</ref> Siddis are primarily [[Sufism|Sufi Muslims]], although some are [[Hindu]]s and others [[Roman Catholic]] Christians.<ref name=\"ali1996j\">{{Citation | title=The African dispersal in the Deccan | author=Shanti Sadiq Ali | year=1996 | publisher=Orient Blackswan | isbn=81-250-0485-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-3CPc22nMqIC | quote=... Among the Siddi families in Karnataka there are Catholics, Hindus and Muslims ... It was a normal procedure for the Portuguese to baptise African slaves ... After living for generations among Hindus they considered themselves to be Hindus ... The Siddi Hindus owe allegiance to Saudmath ...}}</ref> [[Malik Ambar]], a prominent military figure in Indian history at large, remains a figure of veneration to the Siddis of Gujarat.\n\n==Bharuchi and Surti Muslims==\nThere is historical evidence of Arabs and Persians settling along the [[Konkan]]-Gujarat coast as early as the 9th, 8th and perhaps 7th century.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wink|first=Andr\u00e9|title=Al-Hind, the making of the Indo-Islamic world|year=1990|publisher=E.J. Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9004092498|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U7Q3AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA68&dq=arabs,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=arabs%2C%20gujarat&f=false|edition=2. ed., amended.|accessdate=29 January 2014|quote=Up to about the tenth century the largest settlement of Arabs and Persian Muslim traders are not found in Malabar however but rather more to the north in coastal towns of the Konkan and Gujarat, where in pre-Islamic times the Persians dominated the trade with the west. Here the main impetus to Muslim settlement came from the merchants of the Persian Gulf and Oman, with a minority from Hadramaut.}}</ref> Arab traders landed at [[Ghogha]] (located just across the narrow Gulf of [[Cambay]] from [[Bharuch]]/[[Surat]]) around the early seventh century and built a masjid there facing [[Jeruselum]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Schimmel|first=Annemarie|title=Handbuch der Orientalistik.|year=1980|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9004061177|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TYImm1TnemwC&pg=PA65&dq=arabs,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=arabs%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> Thus Gujarat has the oldest mosque in India built between 624-626 C.E. by the Arabs who traded and stayed there. These Arabs and others who settled in [[Bharuch]] and [[Surat]] were sailors, merchants and [[nakhuda]]s, who belonged to various [[South Arabia]]n coastal tribes while others were from the [[Persian Gulf]] and [[Mediterranean]], and large numbers married local women adopting the local Gujarati language and customs over time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dunn|first1=Ross E.|title=The adventures of Ibn Battuta, a Muslim traveler of the fourteenth century|date=2005|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0-520-24385-4|edition=Rev. ed. with a new pref.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Js8qHFVw2gEC&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Many of these \"foreign merchants\" were transient visitors, men of South Arabian and Persian Gulf ports, who migrated in and out of Cambay with the rhythm of the monsoons. But others were men with Persian and fewer Arab patronyms whose families had settled in the town generations, even centuries earlier, intermarrying with Konkani ethnic origins within Gujarats women, and assimilating everyday customs of the Hindu hinterland}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Boyajian|first1=James C.|title=Portuguese trade in Asia under the Habsburgs, 1580-1640|date=2008|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore, Md.|isbn=978-0-8018-8754-3|page=71|edition=Pbk.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=C0lrDYYzMyAC&pg=PA71&dq=gujarat+egypt+trade#v=onepage&q=gujarat%20egypt%20trade&f=false|accessdate=20 February 2015|quote=The history of Indian Ocean trade is a succession of alien merchant diasporas establishing themselves and eventually dominating the region. Gujarat's Muslim community, for example, had originated from traders their mosques, and later the very small settlements of merchants from Turkey, Egypt, Persia and Arabia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Rai|first1=edited by Rajesh|last2=Reeves|first2=Peter|title=The South Asian diaspora transnational networks and changing identities|date=2009|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0-203-89235-0|page=33|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bwJD2WBNtNMC&pg=PA33&dq=gujarat%27s+muslims+egypt#v=onepage&q=gujarat's%20muslims%20egypt&f=false|accessdate=20 February 2015|quote=The social world of the Muslim merchants was complex. The heterogeneity of the Muslim merchant community was made up by the trade but much smaller number of settlers originating from various countries,  as well as by those who were peripatetic traders, coming from places like Persia, Egypt and few from Afghanistan.}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of history, a number of famous Arab travelers, scholars, Sufi-saints and geographers who visited India, have described the presence of thriving Arab-Muslim communities scattered along the Konkan-Gujarat coast.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ashish Vashi & Harit Mehta|title=Gujarat built mosques to draw Arab ships|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Gujarat-built-mosques-to-draw-Arab-ships/articleshow/5582255.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=14 February 2015|quote=The accounts of Arab travellers like Masudi, Istakhari, Ibn Hauqal and others, who visited Gujarat between the 9th and 12th centuries, amply testify to the settlements of Muslims in Cambay and other cities of Gujarat.}}</ref> Suleiman of Basra who reached [[Thana, Maharashtra|Thana]] in 841 AD, observed that the [[Rashtrakuta]] empire which extended from [[Bharuch]] to Chaul during his time, was on friendly terms with the Arabs, and Balhara kings appointed Arab merchant princes as governors and administrators in their vast kingdom.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Acyuta Y\u0101j\u00f1ika, Suchitra Sheth|title=The shaping of modern Gujarat : plurality, Hindutva, and beyond|date=2005|publisher=Penguin Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=0-14400-038-5|page=42|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wmKIiAPgnF0C&pg=PA42&dq=siraf,+gujarat,+persia#v=onepage&q=siraf%2C%20gujarat%2C%20persia&f=false|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ipgrave|first1=Michael|last2=editors|first2=David Marshall|title=Humanity : texts and contexts : Christian and Muslim perspectives : a record of the sixth Building Bridges seminar convened by the Archbishop of Canterbury, National University of Singapore, December 2007|date=2010|publisher=Georgetown University Press|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=978-1-58901-716-0|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/?id=csDpA4gnp-4C&pg=PA40&dq=tajiks,+gujarat+sultanate#v=onepage&q=tajiks%2C%20gujarat%20sultanate&f=false|accessdate=22 February 2015|quote=Memorials can be found in Gujarat honoring Arab Muslims who martyred themselves fighting against Muslim Turks on behalf of Hindu kingdoms. These same kingdoms endowed mosques on behalf of Arab traders.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-link=John Hinnells|editor2-link=Alan Williams|title=Parsis in India and the Diaspora|date=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134067527|pages=51, 52|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ywV9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=sanjan,+madhumati#v=onepage&q=sanjan%2C%20madhumati&f=false|accessdate=29 March 2015|quote=The Chinchani copper plates, datable to the early 10th century,  mention the appointment of Muhammed Sugapita (Sanskrit - 'Madhumati'), a Tajik, as governor of 'Sanyanapattana' (Sanjan port) by the Rashtrakuta king from 878 to 915 AC (Sircar 1962)... This fact is relevant in that it mentions a Muslim administrator controlling the region during the late 9th, and early 10th century... That Sanjan had a large and cosmopolitan population is mentioned in the accounts of travelers as well as the Indian inscriptions and grants mentioned above. While the local tribal populations consisted largely of Kolis and Mahars, the inscriptions list Muslims and Arabs, Panchagaudiya Brahmins, Modha Baniyas and Zoroastrians (Sankalia 1983: 210)}}</ref> [[Ibn Hawqal]], a 10th-century Muslim Arab geographer and chronicler while on his travels observed that mosques flourished in four cities of Gujarat that had Hindu kings, with mosques being found in Cambay, [[Kutch]], Saymur and [[Patan district|Patan]], alluding to an atmosphere where Muslim foreigners were assimilated into the local milieu of medieval Gujarati societies.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wink|first1=Andr\u00e9|title=Al-Hind, the making of the Indo-Islamic world|date=1990|publisher=E.J. Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=90-04-09249-8|page=178|edition=2. ed., amended.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bCVyhH5VDjAC&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=mosques,+in+cambay,+patan,+chaul#v=onepage&q=mosques%2C%20in%20cambay%2C%20patan%2C%20chaul&f=false|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Pearson|first1=M. N.|title=Merchants and rulers in Gujarat : the response to the Portuguese in the sixteenth century|date=1976|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0-520-02809-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/merchantsrulersi0000pear/page/25 25]|url=https://archive.org/details/merchantsrulersi0000pear|url-access=registration|accessdate=14 February 2015|quote=Most of these \"foreign\" Muslims were resident in Gujarat, with their own houses there, and so were in fact subjects of Gujarat, whatever their country of birth, which could be Turkey, Egypt, Arabia or Persia. The heterogeneity of the Muslim population was not confined to merchants, for the sultans made a practice of tempting capable foreigners to Gujarat with handsome salaries, to serve in their armies.}}</ref> His well-known Iranian contemporary [[Estakhri]], the Persian medieval geographer who traveled to Cambay and other regions of Gujarat during the same period, echoed the words spoken by his predecessors alongside his itineraries.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Satish Chandra Misra|title=Muslim Communities in Gujarat: Preliminary Studies in Their History and Social Organization|date=1964|publisher=Asia Publishing House|page=5|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f_AdAAAAMAAJ&q=istakhri,+gujarat&dq=istakhri,+gujarat|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> [[Al-Masudi]], an Arab historian from [[Baghdad]] who was a descendant of [[Abdullah ibn Masud|Abdullah Ibn Mas'ud]], a companion of [[Muhammad]] traveled to Gujarat in 918 C.E, and bore written witness account that more than 10,000 Arab Muslims from [[Siraf]] (Persia) [[Madha]] in Oman, Hadhramaut in [[Yemen]], [[Basra]], Baghdad, and other cities in the Middle East, had settled in the seaport of Chamoor, a port close to [[Bharuch]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Shaykh Gibril Fouad Haddad|title=Abul Hasan Ali Al-Masudi|url=http://sunnah.org/wordpress/2008/07/18/abul-hasan-ali-al-masudi/|website=As-Sunnah Foundation of America|accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cunha|first1=J. Gerson Da|title=Notes on the history and antiquities of Chaul and Bassein|date=1993|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=New Delhi|isbn=8120608453|page=8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xOPlusO8qcAC&pg=PA8&dq=al+masudi,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=al%20masudi%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=23 February 2015|quote=The Lar, also called Lardesa, mentioned by Masudi, is evidently the territory of Gujarat and the Northern Konkan, embracing Broach, Thana, and Chaul, and which name is given by Ptolemy as Larike...As regards Balhara, whom Masudi mentions as the reigning prince to whom Saimur was tributary, it has long been identified as the name of the dynasty which reigned at Valabhi (Valabhipura) in Gujarat, and according to Soliman, a merchant and one of the greatest travellers of his age, was in his time the chief of all the greatest princes in India, the latter acknowledging his preeminence; while the Arabs themselves were shown great favours and enjoyed great privileges in his dominions.}}</ref>\n\nDespite the medieval conquest of Gujarat by [[Alauddin Khalji]] and its annexation to the [[Delhi Sultanate]] in the 13th century, peaceful Islamic settlements appear to have continued under Hindu rule. Bi-lingual Indian inscriptions from [[Somnath]] in Sanskrit and Arabic, make reference to the Arab and Iranian shipowners who constructed mosques in Gujarat from the grants given to Muslims by the [[Vaghela dynasty|Vaghela]] rajput ruler, Arjunadeva.\n<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ray|first1=edited by Bharati|title=Different types of history|date=2009|publisher=Pearson Longman|location=Delhi|isbn=978-8131718186|page=43|edition=1. impr.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NmZzDUYNb0AC&pg=PA43&dq=Arjunadeva,+Gujarat,+grant,#v=onepage&q=Arjunadeva%2C%20Gujarat%2C%20grant%2C&f=false|quote=The person responsible for the construction of the mosque was a sailor and shipowner known as Firuz b. Abu Ibrahim from the state of Hormuz, and in the Arabic version the Muslim ruler to whom these sailors gave their allegiance is recorded as Abu Nusrat Mamud b. Ahmad.... Firuz the shipwner is not the only Persian who appears to have been a person of some standing among the Muslim communities of Gujarat. In Bhadresvar one of the tombstones belongs to one Abu'l-faraj b. Ali, from Siraf, at that time one of the most important ports on the Iranian coast of the Persian Gulf. Another inscription found in Cambay, records the construction of a mosque by Ali b. Shapur in 615/1218-19. The name Shapur shows the Iranian origin of this personage. Other epitaphs are to be found in Cambay belonging to Abi'l-mahasin b. Ardeshir al-Ahwi (d.630/1232-3), Sharaf al-din Murtida b. Mohammad al-Istarabadi, and Ali b Salar b. Ali Yazdi... In the inscription of the mosque at Junagadh, Iraj, the name of a southern Iranian city, near Ramhurmuz, or of the ancestor of Abulqasim b. Ali is also an indication of the Iranian origin of our \"chief of the marchants and shipmasters of the town\". }}</ref> Similar epitaphs mention the arrival of pious Muslim nakhudas from [[Hormuz, Fars|Hormuz]] as well as families from [[Bam, Iran|Bam]] residing in Cambay, and from the discovery of tombstones of personages from [[Siraf]], at the time one of the most important ports on the Iranian coast in the Persian Gulf, suggests altogether that the Muslim community of [[Junagadh]] had a strong and established link with [[Iran]] through the commercial sea routes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bayani-Wolpert|first1=Mehrdad Shokoohy with contributions by Manijeh|last2=Shokoohy|first2=Natalie H.|title=Bhadre\u015bvar ; the oldest Islamic monuments in India|date=1988|publisher=E.J. Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9004083413|page=43|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NmZzDUYNb0AC&pg=PA43&dq=persian+muslims,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=persian%20muslims%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref> The 19th century ''European Gazetteer'' by George Newenham Wright,  corroborates this cultural exchange through the ages as he points out that the Arab inhabitants of [[Mukalla]], capital city of the [[Hadhramaut]] coastal region in [[Yemen]], were known to intermarry with the Mohammedans of [[Kathiawar]] and those resident from other areas of Gujarat.<ref>{{cite book|author1=George Newenham Wright|title=A New and Comprehensive Gazetteer, Volume 5|page=41|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sSQDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA41&dq=Bab-al-Makkah,+surat+gujarat#v=onepage&q=Bab-al-Makkah%2C%20surat%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=The coast of Southern Arabia, was explored in 1833, by Mr. Bird. The people at Mukallah intermarry with the Mohammedans of Katehwar and Gujarat. The sheikh's youngest wife is the daughter of a petty chief in that quarter. The town has rather an imposing appearance as approaching it from the sea.|year=1838}}</ref>\n\nArabic sources speak of the warm reception of the significant immigration of [[Hadhrami people|Hadhrami]] ''s\u0101da'' (descendants of [[Muhammed]]) who settled in [[Surat]] during the [[Gujarat Sultanate]]. Prominent and well respected [[Sayyid|S\u0101da]] who claimed noble descent through [[Abu Bakr al-Aydarus]] (\"Patron Saint of Aden\"),<ref>Jos\u00e9-Marie Bel, Th\u00e9odore Monod, ''Aden: Port mythique du Y\u00e9men'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=TURek_n2BrkC&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=aidrus+aden+mosque+saint&source=bl&ots=ONzOZ0--id&sig=r9xheL_PhnPLydaPdgqBd-hVd-c&hl=en&ei=sd7JSZahNJCo6gOWkOC6Ag&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=7&ct=result pg 99]</ref> were held in high esteem among the people and became established as Arab religious leaderships of local Muslims. Intermarriages with Indian Muslim women were highly sought<ref>{{cite book|first1=ed. by Ulrike Freitag|last1=Ulrike Freitag, William G. Clarence-Smith|title=Hadhrami traders, scholars and statesmen in the Indian Ocean : 1750s - 1960s|date=1997|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden [u.a.]|isbn=9789004107717|page=67|edition=illustrated|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gBTbS4eNGp8C&pg=PA67&dq=surat,+gujarat,+Islam,+muslim,+arab#v=onepage&q=surat%2C%20gujarat%2C%20Islam%2C%20muslim%2C%20arab&f=false|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref> which led to a [[creole peoples|creole]] Hadhrami-Indian community to flourish in Gujarat by the 17th century.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ho|first1=Engseng|title=The graves of Tarim genealogy and mobility across the Indian Ocean|date=2006|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520938694|page=167|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YMcZU0VHdG0C&pg=PA167&lpg=PA167&dq=arabic+sources,+hadhrami,+gujarat#v=onepage&q=arabic%20sources%2C%20hadhrami%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nEarly 14th-century [[Maghrebi]] adventurer, [[Ibn Batuta]], who visited India with his entourage, recalls in his memoirs about Cambay, one of the great emporia of the Indian Ocean that indeed:<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunn|first=Ross E.|title=The adventures of Ibn Battuta, a Muslim traveler of the fourteenth century|year=1986|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520057715|page=218|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZF2spo9BKacC&pg=PA218&dq=gujaratis,+maldives#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20maldives&f=false|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote| [[Cambay]] is one of the most beautiful cities as regards the artistic architecture of its houses and the construction of its mosques. The reason is that the majority of its inhabitants are foreign merchants, who continually build their beautiful houses and wonderful mosques - an achievement in which they endeavor to surpass each other.}}\n\nIn the 17th century, the eminent city of Surat, famous for its cargo export of silk and [[diamonds]] had come on a par with contemporary [[Venice]] and [[Beijing]] which were some of the great mercantile cities of Europe and Asia,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Poros|first1=Maritsa V.|title=Modern migrations : Gujarati Indian networks in New York and London|date=2011|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Stanford, Calif.|isbn=978-0-8047-7222-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_tm_n7uSXT8C&pg=PT30&lpg=PT30&dq=surat,+venice+and+beijing#v=onepage&q=surat%2C%20venice%20and%20beijing&f=false|accessdate=16 February 2015|quote=Indeed, Fernand Braudel likened Surat to some of the great mercantile cities of Europe and Asia, such as Venice and Beijing.... Godinho estimated that Surat's population was more than 100,000, but less with some settlements of people from other cities all over from India residing in the city as well as some foreigners frequenting it for business. He even claimed that it surpasses our \"Evora in grandeur\"}}</ref> and earned the distinguished title, ''Bab al-Makkah'' (Gate of Mecca)because it is one of the great places of the subcontinent where ancient Hindus welcomed Islam and it flourished as time went on.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David Smith|title=Hinduism and modernity|date=2003|publisher=Blackwell|location=Oxford|isbn=0-631-20862-3|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/?id=x-aRSuypah8C&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=Bab-al-Makkah,+surat+gujarat#v=onepage&q=Bab-al-Makkah%2C%20surat%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=Surat was then the place of embarkation of pilgrims to Mecca; known as Bab al-Makkah or  the Gate of Mecca, it was almost a sacred place for the Muslims of India. More to the point it was the main city for foreign imports, where many merchants had their bases,  and all the European trading companies were established. Its population was more than 100, 000.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The journal of Asian studies, Volume 35, Issues 1-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lJtRAQAAIAAJ&q=Bab-al-Makkah,+surat+gujarat&dq=Bab-al-Makkah,+surat+gujarat|accessdate=11 February 2015|quote=For a pious emperor, Surat had more than economic and political importance; it was the port from which the hajj (pilgrimage) ships left Mughal India for the Red Sea. The port was variously known as Bab-al-Makkah, the Bab-ul-Hajj, the Dar-al-Hajj, and the Bandar-i-Mubarak.|year = 1975}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Gujarati Muslims ==\n\nMufti Abdur Rahman Ibn Yusuf Mangera of the UK who is a prominent Islamic Scholar once listed as one of the 500 most influential Muslims in the world, Mufti Ismail Ibn Musa Menk, another prominent Islamic Scholar also of Gujarati descent, South African cricketer [[Hashim Amla]], South African Quran - Bible Scholar [[Ahmed Deedat]], Carabbean eschatologist and Islamic scholar [[Imran N. Hosein]], [[Badruddin Tyabji]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Britain: Discover how South Asians shaped the nation, 1870-1950|url=http://www.open.ac.uk/researchprojects/makingbritain/content/badruddin-tyabji|website=The Open University|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=Badruddin Tyabji was the son of Cambay merchant, Tyab Ali, and his wife, Ameena, the daughter of a rich mullah, Meher Ali.}}</ref> a Congress president and [[Mohammad Ali Jinnah]], the founding father of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jinnah didn't know Urdu, was fluent in Gujarati|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Jinnah-didnt-know-Urdu-was-fluent-in-Gujarati/articleshow/4950044.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=9 February 2015|quote=But Jinnah was fluent in Gujarati. He could read as well as write Gujarati, his mother tongue. Jinnah was a native of Paneli \u2014 not far from Gandhiji's birthplace Porbandar. It is often said the issue of Partition boiled down to these two Kathiawadis.}}</ref> Bollywood is represented by [[Asha Parekh]] who is half Gujarati Muslim, [[Farooq Shaikh]], and [[Sanjeeda Sheikh]]. Famous Indian film score composers include [[Salim-Sulaiman]] Merchant who are [[Ismaili]] [[Shia]] and [[Taher Saifuddin]], who was the 51st [[Da'i al-Mutlaq]] of the [[Dawoodi Bohras]], a sect within [[Shia Islam]]. Famous political activists such as [[Ahmed Timol]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/ahmed-timol |title=Ahmed Timol &#124; South African History Online |publisher=Sahistory.org.za |date= |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> [[Yusuf Dadoo]], and [[Ahmed Kathrada]] played a leading role in the [[anti-apartheid movement]] of South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=34455|title=Review of Kathrada, A. M., No Bread for Mandela: Memoirs of Ahmed Kathrada, Prisoner No. 468/64|first=Antoinette|last=Burton|authorlink=Antoinette Burton|date=1 May 2012|website=www.h-net.org}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sayyid of Gujarat]]\n* [[Khoja]]\n* [[Memon people|Memon]]\n* [[Ismailis]]\n* [[Alavi Bohras]]\n* [[Dawoodi Bohras]]\n*[[Memons (Kathiawar)|Khatiawari Memon]]\n* [[Muslim Rajputs]]\n* [[Islam in India]]\n* [[Gujarat Sultanate]]\n* [[Nakhuda]]\n* [[Jats of Kutch]]\n* [[Pathans of Gujarat]]\n* [[Arabs in India]]\n* [[Al Masudi]]\n* [[Ibn Batuta]]\n* [[Nuruddin ar-Raniri]] from [[Rander]]\n* [[Abu Bakr al-Aydarus]], [[Hadhrami people|Hadhrami]] religious scholar of [[sufism]]\n* [[Ba 'Alawi sada]]\n* [[Abdullah ibn Alawi al-Haddad]]\n* [[Shah e Alam]]\n* [[Wajihuddin Alvi]]\n* [[List of ziyarat locations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Indian Muslim}}\n\n[[Category:Islam in India by location]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of India|*]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Muhajir communities]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of Gujarat|*]]\n[[Category:South African people of Gujarati descent|*]]\n", "name_user": "62.209.23.30", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eJamat Bandi)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gujarati_Muslims"}
